📌 Where to Handle Database Failure Errors in Spring Boot?

When the database connection fails, such as due to:
	•	Network issues (e.g., WiFi turned off)
	•	Cosmos DB being unreachable
	•	Invalid credentials
	•	Timeouts

👉 The application should not expose a stack trace but instead return a structured error response (HTTP 500 - Internal Server Error).

✅ Steps to Handle Database Errors

1️⃣ Catch the CosmosException in Repository Layer
2️⃣ Throw a Custom DatabaseException
3️⃣ Handle DatabaseException in GlobalExceptionHandler
4️⃣ Return a Proper JSON Response (500 Internal Server Error)

📌 1. Catch and Throw a DatabaseException in Repository

📍 Inside CosmosDBRepository.java

import com.azure.cosmos.*;
import org.slf4j.Logger;
import org.slf4j.LoggerFactory;
import org.springframework.stereotype.Repository;
import java.util.List;

/**
 * Cosmos DB Repository for handling database queries.
 */
@Repository
public class CosmosDBRepository {

    private static final Logger logger = LoggerFactory.getLogger(CosmosDBRepository.class);
    private final CosmosContainer cosmosContainer;

    public CosmosDBRepository(CosmosDBConfig cosmosDBConfig) {
        CosmosClient cosmosClient = new CosmosClientBuilder()
                .endpoint(cosmosDBConfig.getEndpoint())
                .key(cosmosDBConfig.getKey())
                .gatewayMode()
                .consistencyLevel(ConsistencyLevel.SESSION)
                .buildClient();

        CosmosDatabase cosmosDatabase = cosmosClient.getDatabase(cosmosDBConfig.getDatabase());
        this.cosmosContainer = cosmosDatabase.getContainer(cosmosDBConfig.getContainer());
    }

    /**
     * Fetches financial institutions, handling DB failures properly.
     *
     * @return List of financial institutions.
     */
    public List<FinancialInstitutionModel> fetchAllInstitutions() {
        try {
            logger.info("Executing query to fetch financial institutions...");
            return cosmosContainer.queryItems(
                    "SELECT * FROM c",
                    new CosmosQueryRequestOptions(),
                    FinancialInstitutionModel.class
            ).stream().toList();

        } catch (CosmosException e) {
            logger.error("❌ Database connection failed! Status Code: {}, Message: {}", e.getStatusCode(), e.getMessage());
            throw new DatabaseException("Database is unavailable. Please try again later.", e); // 🚀 THROWS CUSTOM EXCEPTION
        } catch (Exception e) {
            logger.error("❌ Unexpected Repository Error: ", e);
            throw new DatabaseException("Unexpected database error occurred.", e); // 🚀 THROWS CUSTOM EXCEPTION
        }
    }
}

✅ This ensures that database connection failures are caught and wrapped inside a DatabaseException.
✅ The exception is now thrown upwards to be handled in a global exception handler.

📌 2. Create a DatabaseException Class

📍 Inside DatabaseException.java

/**
 * Custom exception for database failures.
 */
public class DatabaseException extends RuntimeException {

    /**
     * Constructs a DatabaseException with a message.
     * 
     * @param message Error message.
     */
    public DatabaseException(String message) {
        super(message);
    }

    /**
     * Constructs a DatabaseException with a message and cause.
     * 
     * @param message Error message.
     * @param cause The root cause of the error.
     */
    public DatabaseException(String message, Throwable cause) {
        super(message, cause);
    }
}

✅ This helps in differentiating database errors from other errors.

📌 3. Handle the Exception in GlobalExceptionHandler

📍 Inside GlobalExceptionHandler.java

import org.springframework.http.HttpStatus;
import org.springframework.http.ResponseEntity;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.ExceptionHandler;
import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.RestControllerAdvice;
import java.time.LocalDateTime;
import java.util.List;

/**
 * Global Exception Handler for API errors.
 */
@RestControllerAdvice
public class GlobalExceptionHandler {

    /**
     * Handles database failures and returns a 500 error response.
     */
    @ExceptionHandler(DatabaseException.class)
    public ResponseEntity<ErrorResponseDTO> handleDatabaseException(DatabaseException ex) {
        return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR)
                .body(new ErrorResponseDTO(
                        "500",
                        "Database Error",
                        List.of(new ErrorDetailDTO("CosmosDB", ex.getMessage())),
                        LocalDateTime.now()
                ));
    }
}

✅ This ensures that DatabaseException is handled globally and returns a 500 Internal Server Error.

